  .bottom-cta h2 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 3vw, 2.4rem); font-weight: 800; margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .bottom-cta p { color: #aaa; margin: 0 0 32px; font-size: 1.05rem; }
</style>

<!-- 01 HERO + TRUST BAR (unified ServiceHero) -->
<ServiceHero
  title="Oven & Range Repair Across Southern California"
  subtitle="From a Wolf dual-fuel that won't hold temperature to a KitchenAid with a failed bake element, our technicians carry parts for the ranges SoCal kitchens actually have. Same-day across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino & Riverside counties."
  heroImageTitle="Oven & Range Repair"
/>

<!-- 03 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01, About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Southern California kitchens run the full range. So do we.</h2>
        <p>Oven and range calls across SoCal cover more ground than in most regions. You have the standard GE and KitchenAid ranges in mid-century homes and rental units from Burbank to Riverside. You have the 48-inch Wolf dual-fuel ranges and Thermador steam ovens in the renovated kitchens of Bel Air, Newport Coast, Pasadena estates, and Pacific Palisades. And increasingly, the boutique European brands, LaCanche, BlueStar, Bertazzoni, ILVE, in the kitchens of serious home cooks who wanted something you can't buy at Best Buy.</p>
        <p>Our technicians work across all of them. The repair skills for a Wolf and a Whirlpool overlap more than you'd think, igniters, temperature sensors, bake elements, control boards, but the parts are brand-specific and need to be OEM. A generic igniter on a Viking range fits poorly and often fails within months. We source directly from authorized suppliers for every professional brand we service.</p>
        <p>The most common oven call across SoCal: the oven heats but the temperature is off, food is undercooked or overcooked at the set temperature. That's almost always the temperature sensor. Second most common: gas burner that won't ignite. Third: the self-clean cycle locked the door and it won't release. We carry parts for all three on the van.</p>
        <div class="tip-safety">
          <div class="tip-label">🔥 Gas Safety Note</div>
          <p>If you smell gas near your range, turn off the burners, open windows, and leave the space before calling anyone. We handle gas appliance repairs on the appliance side, but a gas smell that persists after the burners are off warrants a call to SoCalGas at 1-800-427-2200 before scheduling a repair appointment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">Same Day Oven &amp; Range Repair</div>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="btn-cta">Call Now, We Pick Up</a>
        <a href="/book/" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top:-4px;">Book Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Fri 7am–9pm · Sat Mon–Sat 8am–8pm · Sun closed · Phone answered 24/7</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>$89 diagnostic, applied to repair</li>
          <li>90-day warranty on parts &amp; labor</li>
          <li>OEM parts for all brands</li>
          <li>Wolf, Thermador, Viking, LaCanche</li>
          <li>Written estimate before we start</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 RANGE TYPES -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Range &amp; Oven Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every configuration in SoCal kitchens</h2>
    <p class="lead">Gas, electric, dual-fuel, wall ovens, rangetops, the failure modes vary by type.</p>
    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Gas Range</div>
        <h3>Gas Ranges &amp; Rangetops</h3>
        <p>Most common in SoCal homes. Burner ignition issues are the most frequent calls, won't ignite, constant clicking, uneven flame. Gas oven section has its own igniter, temperature sensor, and sometimes a broil element.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Electric</div>
        <h3>Electric Ranges &amp; Wall Ovens</h3>
        <p>Common in condos without gas service. Bake element and broil element failures are primary repairs. Temperature sensor and control board issues are also frequent. Wall ovens, single and double, serviced the same way.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Dual-Fuel</div>
        <h3>Dual-Fuel Ranges</h3>
        <p>Gas burners over an electric oven, the preferred configuration for serious home cooks. Wolf, Thermador, and Viking all offer dual-fuel lines. Repairs on both sections require brand-specific OEM parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Convection</div>
        <h3>Convection &amp; Steam Ovens</h3>
        <p>Convection adds a fan motor, an additional failure point. Steam ovens (Thermador, Miele, Wolf) add a water reservoir and steam injection system. More components, different diagnostic approach.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>
    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Oven Won't Heat</h3>
        <p>On an electric oven, a burned-out bake element is most common, you can often see the break or burn mark. On a gas oven, the igniter glows to open the gas valve; when it weakens, the valve never opens. We carry bake elements and igniters for the major brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Temperature Inaccurate</h3>
        <p>The temperature sensor (probe) measures cavity temperature and tells the control board when to cycle heat. When it drifts or fails, the oven consistently runs hot or cold. Most common explanation for food that never cooks correctly at the set temperature, and a quick fix once confirmed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Bakes Unevenly / Hot Spots</h3>
        <p>A partially failed bake element heats unevenly, the section near the failure underheats. A drifting temperature sensor causes the oven to cycle incorrectly. We run a temperature test across multiple positions before concluding the cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Broiler Not Working</h3>
        <p>On an electric range, the broil element is separate from the bake element and fails independently. On a gas range, the broiler uses a separate igniter or pilot. Usually a straightforward element or igniter replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Gas Burner Won't Ignite</h3>
        <p>First check whether the burner cap and ports are clean, clogged ports from food spills are the most common cause. If clean, the spark electrode, igniter module, or gas valve needs attention. A burner that clicks continuously without lighting almost always has a faulty spark electrode.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Self-Clean Door Locked Shut</h3>
        <p>The self-clean cycle locks the door for safety. When it ends but the door won't release, the door lock motor assembly has usually failed. Cutting power at the breaker and waiting for full cooldown sometimes releases it, if not, the lock motor needs replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Oven Door Issues</h3>
        <p>A door that won't close fully, has a broken hinge, or a cracked door gasket loses heat constantly, the oven runs non-stop trying to maintain temperature and still underperforms. Door hinges and gaskets are serviceable parts we carry for residential and professional brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Control Board / Error Codes</h3>
        <p>Modern ranges display error codes pointing to specific failed components. Our technicians are current on diagnostic codes for Thermador, Wolf, Miele, Samsung, and LG. We verify the board is the actual issue before recommending it, control boards are expensive and other components can produce similar symptoms.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05.5 SUB-SERVICES NAV -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Detailed Failure-Mode Diagnostics</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Specific oven problems covered in depth</h2>
    <p class="lead">Each of these sub-services walks through the diagnostic logic, parts cost, and field-tested honest opinion for the most common oven failure modes we see across SoCal.</p>
    <div class="problems-grid">
      <a href="/services/oven-repair/not-heating/" class="problem-card" style="display:block; text-decoration:none; color:inherit;">
        <h3>Oven Not Heating →</h3>
        <p>About 50% of gas not-heating calls are a weak igniter. Test current before replacing the gas valve. Element resistance, RTD sensor, induction range bake-element distinction. $200 to $1,200 typical.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/services/oven-repair/temperature-off/" class="problem-card" style="display:block; text-decoration:none; color:inherit;">
        <h3>Oven Temperature Off →</h3>
        <p>Often resolved without parts via the user calibration menu. RTD sensor drift diagnostic, pro-style vs mid-tier tolerance expectations, smart-oven app vs sensor. $89 walkthrough through $720 sensor or board.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/services/oven-repair/door-issues/" class="problem-card" style="display:block; text-decoration:none; color:inherit;">
        <h3>Oven Door Issues →</h3>
        <p>Hinge sag is the most common (year 7 to 10), pro-style hinges 2 to 3x mid-tier cost. Glass replacement, gasket failure, double-oven proactive hinge inversion. $200 to $1,800 range.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/services/oven-repair/self-clean-problems/" class="problem-card" style="display:block; text-decoration:none; color:inherit;">
        <h3>Oven Self-Clean Problems →</h3>
        <p>The single biggest oven repair trigger we see. F1/F2/F3 codes after self-clean, locked door, control board damage. Why we recommend manual cleaning. $260 to $2,200 range, pro-style not immune.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

