<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>
    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Bel Air (LA County) · Wolf 48" Dual-Fuel</div>
        <h3>"Oven runs 75 degrees cold, bread never comes out right"</h3>
        <p>Temperature sensor failure on a Wolf dual-fuel. The probe had drifted well outside spec, reading about 75°F below actual temperature. The customer had been compensating by adjusting the set temperature, that's the wrong fix. The sensor is the issue.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced temperature probe with OEM Wolf part. Calibrated with an independent thermometer across three test cycles. Oven confirmed accurate to within 5°F at 350°, 400°, and 450°. Customer had been compensating for about eight months, the repair took 45 minutes.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · Bertazzoni 36" Gas Range</div>
        <h3>"Front left burner won't light, clicks constantly"</h3>
        <p>Spark electrode failure on a Bertazzoni gas range in a Newport Beach coastal kitchen, the electrode had cracked at the ceramic insulator, causing intermittent sparking that couldn't produce a consistent arc. Coastal salt air accelerates ceramic insulator cracking on these units. Parts are brand-specific and not stocked by generic suppliers.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Sourced and replaced OEM Bertazzoni spark electrode assembly. Verified ignition on all six burners before leaving. Also cleaned burner caps and ports, one other burner had partial port blockage that would have caused a similar issue within a few months.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills (LA County) · Thermador Pro Grand Steam</div>
        <h3>"Self-clean ran, oven won't unlock, two days now"</h3>
        <p>Door lock motor failure after a self-clean cycle. The cycle ran to completion but the door lock solenoid failed to retract, the oven cooled but the door stayed locked. Cutting power at the breaker didn't release it, confirming the lock motor had seized.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced door lock motor assembly with OEM Thermador part. Tested door release after installation, ran a short self-clean cycle to verify the lock-unlock sequence functioned correctly. Two-hour repair, customer had been without the oven for two days.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · KitchenAid Wall Oven KOSE500ESS</div>
        <h3>"Bottom of oven scorches, top is underdone"</h3>
        <p>Partial bake element failure, about a third of the element had burned through, leaving one section overheating and the rest underperforming. Some homeowners misdiagnose this as a sensor issue, but a visual inspection of the element makes it obvious.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced bake element with OEM KitchenAid part. Tested at 375°F, even temperature distribution confirmed across the full oven cavity. 30-minute repair once part was identified.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

